WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:11.480
He may have been a major player in the pages
of Marvel Comics for over half a century,

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:15.950
but it was only recently that Captain America
became the poster boy for the Marvel Cinematic

00:00:15.950 --> 00:00:16.950
Universe.

00:00:16.950 --> 00:00:20.860
The quintessential hero, it’s almost impossible
to imagine what kind of fight would force

00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:23.640
him to turn against his fellow Avengers.

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.640
But you might be surprised to find out that
the comic book history of the squeaky clean,

00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:30.050
star spangled Boy Scout is as dark as they
come.

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:34.370
And if fans of comic book movies think their
superhero blockbusters are getting a little

00:00:34.370 --> 00:00:39.520
too dark, violent, or serious, they’d better
hope these famous moments from Captain America’s

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.160
history are never adapted.

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:44.560
But they’re still stories every fan should
know, so we’ve made them the focus of our

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:53.530
latest Docu Series: The Shockingly DARK History
of Captain America.

00:00:53.530 --> 00:00:56.160
The Original Captain America

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:00.469
Looking back now, it makes perfect sense for
Cap to have made his debut in a solo comic,

00:01:00.469 --> 00:01:02.560
punching out Adolf Hitler on the front cover.

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:07.789
But remember: the first comic was released
in 1941, a full year before the United States

00:01:07.789 --> 00:01:09.600
even entered World War 2.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:13.670
So to a large part of the American public
who weren’t looking to go to war with Germany,

00:01:13.670 --> 00:01:18.340
the star-spangled hero made his debut knocking
a foreign head of state unconscious.

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:22.340
The move proved controversial, since the world
didn’t know just what Hitler’s Third Reich

00:01:22.340 --> 00:01:27.880
was up to, but it didn’t stop Timely Comics,
the original publishers, since the comics

00:01:27.880 --> 00:01:33.120
that followed were huge successes, showing
Cap knocking out Nazis of all shapes and sizes.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:37.530
The stories inside the comics were a bit different,
but remember: Steve Rogers and his sidekick

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:43.350
Bucky Barnes were American soldiers first
– so while DC’s Batman was snapping criminals’

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:47.950
necks, Cap and Bucky were wiping out Nazi
soldiers one grenade at a time.

00:01:47.950 --> 00:01:52.670
It was war, sure, but that didn’t stop Marvel
from rewriting history years later to keep

00:01:52.670 --> 00:01:58.380
Cap’s killing to a minimum.

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:00.920
Captain America Goes To Hell

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.840
Things got weird with Captain America almost
immediately.

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:07.530
Once the war came to an end, the writers had
to find a new purpose for Cap – and had

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:08.899
serious trouble doing it.

00:02:08.899 --> 00:02:14.489
After just 70 issues, Cap and his famous enemy
Red Skull had fought in so many weird places,

00:02:14.489 --> 00:02:17.040
there was just one left to go: Hell.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:21.060
Descending into the underworld in “Captain
America’s Weird Tales” and forced to kill

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:26.279
Red Skull or remain there for God, Cap came
through, unsure if it was all a dream – or

00:02:26.279 --> 00:02:27.640
completely real.

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:32.439
Not surprising, it was the final issue he
would appear in before joining plenty of his

00:02:32.439 --> 00:02:34.900
fellow superheroes on the shelf.

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:37.049
